ned to familiarise parliamentarians with the Convention and the Optional Protocol and describes what parliamentarians can do to ensure effective implementation of the Convention. Countries around the world have progressed enormously on gender equality through the hard work of women\u2019s organisations and their respective national women\u2019s machineries. They have also progressed because high profile champions such as parliamentarians have recognised the importance of gender equality and the protection of women\u2019s rights and made the implementation of the Convention their personal mission. This publication is timely as it coincides with the 60th Anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. It is ironic that sixty years down the road some of our Pacific nations have yet to ratify CEDAW. Only New Zealand, Solomon Islands and Vanuatu have ratified the Optional Protocol. In addition to this Pacific women only make up 3.1% of Pacific Parliamentarians (excluding Australia and New Zealand), with five of our Pacific countries have no women representatives at all. It is obvious that the Pacific still has a long way to go. The contents of this pocket guide has drawn on other important publications on the Convention such as the \u201cCEDAW Handbook for Parliamentarians\u201d by the IPU, the \u201cCEDAW Roadmap\u201d by the Regional Rights Resource Team (RRRT) and \u201cCEDAW Legislative Compliance in Nine Pacific Island Countries\u201d by UNDP Pacific Centre and UNIFEM. Our thanks goes to them for their work on this important convention. We hope that this booklet will help towards an understanding of CEDAW and what can be done to advance gender equality. Feleti P Teo Acting Secretary General Pacific Islands Forum Secretariat CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 3 Table of Contents Foreword 1 InTroduCTIon 5 whAT Is CedAw?", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: