spect and dignity and does not suffer from discrimination. Guide outlines measures to ensure that national laws, policies, actions, programmes and budgets reflect the principles and obligations in CEDAW. Legislators are recognised by the community as national leaders. In this context, members of Pacific parliaments and congresses can also be active in raising awareness about the standards for the treatment of women which are contained in CEDAW. In the Pacific, each country is unique in its culture and local context. The method your country chooses to promote gender equality will take account of your own national circumstances. CEDAW can be a key framework to guide local work directed at promoting women\u2019s equality. In any case, the long-term goal remains the same \u2013 namely, to ensure that every Pacific person, whether man or women, is treated with respect and dignity and does not suffer from discrimination. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 7 D iscrimination against women is defined as \u201c\u2026any distinction, exclusion or restriction made on the basis of sex which has the effect or purpose of impairing or nullifying the recognition, enjoyment or exercise by women, irrespective of their marital status, on a basis of equality of men and women, of human rights and fundamental freedoms in the political, economic, social, cultural, civil or any other field.\u201d 1. www.un.org/rights/50/decla/htm 2. www2.ohchr.ch/htm/menu3/b/a_ccpr.htm 3. www.unesco.org/education/pdf/social_E_pdf what is CedAw? CEDAW is the short name given to the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women. The Convention is commonly regarded by many as the international bill of rights for women. CEDAW was adopted in 1979 by the members of the United Nations following decades of national, regional and international efforts to promote and protect the rights of the world\u2019s women. A CEDAW Optional Protocol was developed in 2000. CEDAW builds on the protections already included in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR),1 the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR),2 and the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights (ICESCR).3 These three UN human rights agreements are commonly referred to as the International Bill of Rights. CedAw in Brief CEDAW seeks to comprehensively address women\u2019s rights to equality in all areas of women\u2019s lives, including civil, political, economic, social and cultural. CEDAW also provides a comprehensive description of discrimination against women and requires state parties to take all the necessary measures to eliminate such discrimination. Although the provisions in the International Bill of Rights also apply to women, CEDAW was developed in recognition of the fact that the basic rights of vulnerable members of society like women are still not fully applied in practice.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6dbbed7c-3390-4156-9e7b-0532374ac558": {"__data__": {"id_": "6dbbed7c-3390-4156-9e7b-0532374ac558", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "249558a0d64efdd41d4eb46dd3ec3d434678b5d090269475f037ff3c567e0a6a"}, "2": {"node_id": "8ec6aa5b-92ec-4bc7-92b6-b7f55a975b49", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "659d0659bde5e9b58600236e4dd3f420dbbfa8d4682b6f808377afae812893a1"}}, "hash": "73682ad62276c6dd66c2f735fa6d4c67752d9773a0ca461fce1fe2840d634f82", "text": "Developing a more specific convention is intended to ensure that government attention and resources are devoted to more effectively tackling women\u2019s issues. In the Pacific region, 13 countries of the 16 Pacific Island Forum countries have ratified or acceded to CEDAW. As of 1 January 2008, 185 countries throughout the world have ratified or acceded to the Convention. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 8 Highlights the appropriate measures to bring", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e4e750e4-b600-4040-b929-352974dfac53": {"__data__": {"id_": "e4e750e4-b600-4040-b929-352974dfac53", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1118a426059d48736c03c4fbd4bcd07bba933abc139940542e27908cb1977dcb"}, "3": {"node_id": "a9d3c590-c266-41ee-83b1-cb26380e9394", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dc02f064996fccfd6637acbb5e0001d01454fbcc4e99580a2fd46559fef80fee"}}, "hash": "4d151ba6b71a0003dbf8d16e14a6bb42d8882ba3c3eedbc23ecd880b15aff825", "text": "about the advancement of women. These include constitutional, legislative, administrative and other measures, including special temporary measures. Highlights what States must do to protect women\u2019s rights in public and political life. Highlights the commitments States must make to eliminate discrimination in education, employment. health, economic, social and cultural life. Highlights what States must do to accord women equality with men before the law, in the exercise of legal rights and in marriage and family law. Administrative reporting under CEDAW. The following table summarises the major provisions of CEDAW. The different colours in the table highlight the different areas requiring State attention: Table 1 : Summary of CEDAW Provisions 4 Article Area/subject Article 1 Definition of discrimination against women Article 2 Obligations of state parties Article 3 Advancement of women at all levels Article 4 Temporary special measures (affirmative action) Article 5 Modification of culture and family responsibilities Article 6 Suppression of prostitution Article 7 Women in public and political life Article 8 Women at international level Article 9 Women\u2019s nationality Article 10 Women and education Article 11 Women in formal employment Article 12 Women and health care Article 13 Women in economic and social life Article 14 Women in rural areas Article 15 Women and the law Article 16 Women and private life Article 17-30 Administrative (reporting, etc) 4. Taken from RRRT Roadmap to Reporting CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 9 CedAw optional protocol An Optional Protocol is a legal instrument related to an existing treaty, in this case CEDAW, which addresses issues not covered by the treaty or insufficiently developed in the treaty. It is described as \u2018Optional\u2019 because states are not obliged to become party to it, even if they have ratified or acceded to the related convention. The Optional CEDAW Protocol describes: (1) A communications procedure, which enables individuals or groups to submit claims of violations of rights protected under the Convention, to the Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women, subject to certain criteria being met; (2) An inquiry procedure, enabling the Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women to initiate inquiries into situations of grave or systematic violations of women\u2019s rights. The Optional Protocol was developed because CEDAW itself does include a monitoring system, apart from the regular country reports that states must submit. Under the original Convention, individuals and other groups have no way of making complaints on human rights violations that occur in their country. Only three Forum Pacific Island countries have ratified the Optional Protocol, namely New Zealand, Solomon Islands and Vanuatu. Notably, even where a state has ratified CEDAW, for the Optional Protocol to be relied upon by citizens, the state must separately have ratified it. E ssentially, the Optional Protocol is a backup to domestic laws and policies. Sometimes domestic laws and policies have some gaps whereby women find they cannot exercise or protect their rights. The Optional Protocol provides for a complaints mechanism that ensures protection. Committee on the elimination of discrimination against women CEDAW established the Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women, an expert body which is tasked to oversee its implementation. The Committee is composed of 23 members from around the world who are responsible for monitoring the progress made by states in implementing the Convention. The Committee examines the regular reports that every State Party is legally bound to submit on the measures it has taken to give effect to the provisions of the Convention (see page 19 for more on reporting). The Committee is also empowered to make suggestions and recommendations based on the examination of reports and information received from State Parties. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 10 ratifying Countries CedAw Table 2: Forum Island Countires which have ratified CEDAW and the Optional Procol optional protocol Australia 28-Jul-83 Cook Islands 1-Oct-85 via NZ Fiji 28-Aug-95 Kiribati 17-Apr-04 Marshall islands 2-Mar-06 Micronesia (Federated States of) 1-Sep-04 Nauru New Zealand 10-Jan-85 7-Sep-00 Niue 1-Oct-85 via NZ Palau Papua New Guinea 12-Jan-95 Samoa 25-Sep-92 Solomon Islands 6-May-02 6-May-02 Tonga Tuvalu 6-Oct-99 Vanuatu 8-Sep-95 17-May-07 CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 11 encouraging ratification A state becomes party to CEDAW by ratifying or acceding to it. Sometimes states ratify a convention, but submit \u201creservations\u201d which limit the application of the convention.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a9d3c590-c266-41ee-83b1-cb26380e9394": {"__data__": {"id_": "a9d3c590-c266-41ee-83b1-cb26380e9394", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1118a426059d48736c03c4fbd4bcd07bba933abc139940542e27908cb1977dcb"}, "2": {"node_id": "e4e750e4-b600-4040-b929-352974dfac53", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4d151ba6b71a0003dbf8d16e14a6bb42d8882ba3c3eedbc23ecd880b15aff825"}}, "hash": "dc02f064996fccfd6637acbb5e0001d01454fbcc4e99580a2fd46559fef80fee", "text": "Ideally, states will ratify CEDAW and its Optional Protocol with no reservations. ratifying CedAw Even if women\u2019s rights are protected in the constitution and other laws, nonetheless, ratifying an international convention like CEDAW sends an important signal to citizens and to the international community about your commitment to take all measures necessary to promote the rights", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b2e31180-c7d8-45ce-a496-a9b2f93ea448": {"__data__": {"id_": "b2e31180-c7d8-45ce-a496-a9b2f93ea448", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0b456ff0d859afa9917f5efe9b337a0aa66182f82674ac2c5b281cd7e6af75e9"}, "3": {"node_id": "0d02bdd5-0ef4-4786-ad09-11b2ec6e82e6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c5c5d9c4801b78568c02747af2a29757e6a43b22bffce5f05e1647ccf3c37da3"}}, "hash": "43619d773cc619cea2292366e0feb359c9cc430d5b31fcea9f6196bc2b7799f4", "text": "of women and eliminate all forms of discrimination against women. A state which only signs a convention is not legally bound to give effect to its provisions. However, a signature at least creates an obligation to refrain in good faith from acts that would defeat the purpose of the convention. Conventions are often signed first by a member of the Executive, for example, the President, Prime Minister or Foreign Minister. The gap between signature and ratification then provides time to obtain approval of the convention at the national level, usually by submitting the convention to review and comment by the legislature. Formal ratification occurs when the government deposits an \u201cinstrument of ratification\u201d with the Secretary-General of the United Nations. Acceding to a convention simply refers to a ratification that occurs after a convention has come into force. Usually the Executive, that is the government of the day, has the power to ratify or accede to international agreements. However, ratification at the international level should not be confused with ratification at the national level. In some countries, particularly those with presidential-style systems, there may be domestic legal requirements to meet before the government can consent to an international treaty or convention that will bind it at the international level. For example, Congress may be required to pass a resolution empowering the President to ratify the convention. N auru, Palau and Tonga have not ratified CEDAW. Only New Zealand, Solomon Islands and Vanuatu have ratified both CEDAW and the Optional Protocol. Legislators who are members of Government can be active in encouraging Cabinet colleagues to ratify CEDAW and its Optional Protocol. The Minister of Justice, Minister for Foreign Affairs and/or Attorney General often lead the way. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 12 reservations Article 28 of CEDAW permits ratification or accession to be made subject to \u201creservations\u201d. A reservation is a formal declaration that the State does not accept part of the convention as binding. It is clear in international law, however, that no reservation can be made which is incompatible with the convention\u2019s object and purpose. Ideally, your state will ratify CEDAW completely. However, sometimes a State will lodge a reservation because they feel that implementation of an Article may take time and they do not want to be in breach of the convention in the meantime. This highlights the importance of constantly reviewing any reservations your country may have lodged at the time it ratified CEDAW. The CEDAW Committee\u2019s reporting guidelines require states to explain any reservation to any article of the Convention and to justify their continued maintenance. States may withdraw reservations at any time. Withdrawals must be formulated in writing, and signed by the Head of State, Head of Government or Minister of Foreign Affairs, or person having powers for such purposes. What can you do as a Parliamentarian? If your country has not ratified CEDAW or the Optional Protocol, you can: Put an oral or written question to the Government \ufffd during\ufffdQuestion\ufffdTime\ufffdto\ufffdfind\ufffdout\ufffdwhether\ufffdratification/\ufffd \ufffd accession\ufffdis\ufffdunder\uff