ationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0b456ff0d859afa9917f5efe9b337a0aa66182f82674ac2c5b281cd7e6af75e9"}, "2": {"node_id": "b2e31180-c7d8-45ce-a496-a9b2f93ea448", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "43619d773cc619cea2292366e0feb359c9cc430d5b31fcea9f6196bc2b7799f4"}}, "hash": "c5c5d9c4801b78568c02747af2a29757e6a43b22bffce5f05e1647ccf3c37da3", "text": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 13 Implementing CedAw Ratifying CEDAW is a first step towards improving the lives of women, but much more needs to be done in practical terms if women are to really benefit from the protections provided in the Convention. Focussing attention and resources on implementation of the Convention is essential to ensure that women\u2019s rights are protected and promoted in reality. legislative Compliance In practical terms, States who are party to CEDAW need to bring their domestic laws and policies into line with the provisions of CEDAW. This is a key opportunity for members of Pacific parliaments and congresses to get involved in ensuring that CEDAW is meaningfully implemented. In 2007, the UNDP Pacific Centre and UNIFEM produced a comprehensive handbook to assist Pacific legislators to assess whether the laws are in compliance with CEDAW called \u201cTranslating CEDAW Into Law: CEDAW Legislative Compliance in Nine Pacific Island Countries.\u201d The handbook included a list of 113 questions which legislators can ask to check whether national laws comply with CEDAW. This list of questions \u2013 referred to in the region as \u201clegislative compliance indicators\u201d \u2013 is included at Annex 1. Legislators are encouraged to familiarise themselves with the Pacific legislative compliance", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ed02c9a8-3941-434c-9c23-62e8780f01d1": {"__data__": {"id_": "ed02c9a8-3941-434c-9c23-62e8780f01d1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "89067c25f5590876afcf30edbaefa9afd498117f9e9b2e8a96520552c2a335fb"}, "3": {"node_id": "fa7b496c-9dcb-4b53-96fc-eecd8c242da7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2a0558b88083cbbb138a9fecd79f768ca627ede364283e37ff689907d9a6a731"}}, "hash": "a58473ddb704656ce90bf1bbbe89e073b759848fcebcbec938649cdcb4dfc980", "text": "indicators as they provide a good starting point for questions in parliament. They also provide practical guidance on what issues to look for when assessing Bills or regulations. When CEDAW is first ratified, the Government should task the Attorney General or Justice Ministry with undertaking a legislative review of all existing legislation to ensure that it is compliant with the provisions of CEDAW. All laws must be included in the review. Laws which deal with discrimination may be a priority, but it is important to remember that even laws which appear to be \u201cgender-neutral\u201d can have a differential impact on men and women. A ffirmative action measures to address inequalities should be considered. For example, throughout the Pacific, there have been suggestions that laws be enacted to reserve seats in the legislature for women or to introduce women\u2019s quotas into political parties. Such temporary measures would go some way to implementing CEDAW Article 7 which promotes equality in political life. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 14 At a minimum, any legislative review needs to examine existing laws in order to: Identify those laws which are discriminatory; Identify existing legal gaps or loopholes; Identify situations in which: Inconsistencies between different kinds of laws (constitutional, penal, civil, administrative) result in gender bias; Administrative procedures discriminating against women undermine the law; and Harmful traditional practices and negative customs run counter to existing law. Once this initial analysis is done: Where laws need to be updated, amendments should be tabled in the legislature as a priority; Where new laws are needed to protect or promote women\u2019s rights in accordance with CEDAW, they need to be developed participatorily \u2013 with a chance for public input. Draft Bills need to be referred to a relevant parliamentary committee, which can hold public hearings. Specific invitations to provide evidence and advice at such hearings should be sent to community groups with expertise on women\u2019s issues. Tapping their experiences can be useful in ensuring that legislation properly deals with your local context. Committee hearings provide a great opportunity for legislators to consider a Bill in more detail and to discuss amongst themselves whether it achieves what it sets out to do. Non-Cabinet or non-government members can be active in promoting CEDAW legislative compliance. Questions can be asked during Question Time to draw the attention of the government to key areas where you believe action needs to be taken, for example, amending discriminatory rape laws or enacting anti-discrimination legislation. Members of the Opposition can also consider developing a Private Member\u2019s Bill on topics you believe are important. If the government does not want to take action on an issue, a Private Member\u2019s Bill can be a strategic way of prodding them into action. L egislators can draw on specialist Pacific NGOs and community groups for assistance with legislative reviews and analysis. Many women\u2019s organisations in the Pacific are capable of providing legal inputs on Bills. Most such groups will provide advice and assistance for free, and increasingly there are organisations in the Pacific, such as the Regional Rights and Resources Team, that can provide legislative assistance to Pacific legislators. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 15 What can you do as a Parliamentarian? If you are a Member of Government: Ensure\ufffdthat\ufffdall\ufffdpolicy\ufffdand\ufffdlegislative\ufffdmatters\ufffdthat\ufffdare \ufffd \ufffd proposed\ufffdare\ufffdCEDAW\ufffdcompliant.\ufffdYour\ufffdannual\ufffd\ufffd \ufffd \ufffd legislative\ufffdprogramme\ufffdshould\ufffdspecifically\ufffdidentify \ufffd \ufffd CEDAW\ufffdcompliance\ufffdas\ufffdan\ufffdobjective.\ufffd Ensure that all existing legislation is reviewed to \ufffd ensure\ufffdit\ufffdcomplies\ufffdwith\ufffdCEDAW.\ufffd\ufffdThe\ufffdLegislative\ufffd\ufffd \ufffd \ufffd Compliance\ufffdIndicators\ufffddeveloped\ufffdby\ufffdUNDP\ufffdand \ufffd \ufffd UNIFEM\ufffdprovide\ufffda\ufffduseful\ufffdreference\ufff