r-equality perspective in all policy areas.\u201d Throughout the Pacific, most countries have established a Women\u2019s Ministry or its equivalent. However, by and large, these bodies are provided with only minimal staff, often with limited expertise on women\u2019s issues, and are given very few resources to do their work. The Beijing Platform for Action recommends that women\u2019s machineries are located at the highest possible level in the government, falling under the responsibility of a Cabinet minister. Members of Cabinet should seek to action this recommendation, and non-executive legislators can push for this to happen via the strategic use of Question Time. Most Pacific Island countries have developed specific national women\u2019s policies or plans. Where your country has not, you may want to use Question Time to find out why and whether there is any plan by the Government to develop one in future. A national women\u2019s action plan will set out the government\u2019s programme of activities for implementing CEDAW\u2019s provisions and achieving better outcomes for women. The plan will also identify the resources needed and the bodies responsible for taking action. The plan should guide ALL government agencies \u2013 not just the national women\u2019s ministry. F ind out what your national policies and programmes are for women. Call your gender focal point. This could be the Women\u2019s Desk Officer or the Ministry for Women or a Committee on Gender Equality, or their equivalent. Ask them for a copy of your national policy and programmes document for women.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4450ceb1-590f-46f6-b561-67ea26542930": {"__data__": {"id_": "4450ceb1-590f-46f6-b561-67ea26542930", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-