of Action. Essentially, every government has an overarching strategic document that guides and informs the policies of the government. What can you do as a Parliamentarian? If you are a Member of Cabinet: Ensure that the Women\u2019s Ministry/Department is located at the highest possible level in the Government. Ensure that a suf\ufb01cient budget allocation is provided to the Women\u2019s Ministry/Department and to other departments to implement CEDAW-related activities. Use Question Time to: Find out whether a National Women\u2019s Action", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5d9a5395-f24f-4060-ac63-03e22a6f871a": {"__data__": {"id_": "5d9a5395-f24f-4060-ac63-03e22a6f871a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "14bea8877f7129ff41076b21b4cbb38e3725dfb732a1dc5eff2852eab30c9411"}}, "hash": "14bea8877f7129ff41076b21b4cbb38e3725dfb732a1dc5eff2852eab30c9411", "text": "Plan has been developed and if not, why? If a plan has been developed, encourage the submission of the plan to the legislature for consideration and comment. Ideally the plan should be referred to a Parliamentary Committee and a public hearing undertaken to enable the public to comment. Find out whether the National Development Plan properly deals with CEDAW issues. Ask follow up questions regarding the implementation of the Women\u2019s Action Plan and CEDAW elements of any National Development Plan. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 19 reporting on CedAw Once CEDAW is ratified by a country, Article 18 requires that a report is submitted to the CEDAW Committee on implementation of CEDAW. An initial report is due at the end of the first year and updates should follow every four years or when requested by the CEDAW Committee. national reports All countries which have ratified CEDAW must submit a State Report which covers the legislative, judicial and administrative measures that the State has implemented as part of their obligations under CEDAW. It is also an opportunity for the State Party to take stock of the current situation of women, compare the current situation to that of the past (via previous national reports) and identify areas that require reform to ensure compliance with the convention. States must also explain any reservation to any article of the convention and to justify their continued maintenance. The main aims of a State Party Report to CEDAW are to: Provide a record of performance of the Government according to the standards of CEDAW; Identify problems and obstacles to women's equality and suggest solutions so they can be addressed; Identify best practices; Identify priorities for the next four years; Provide an opportunity for the State to show good faith in living up to its obligations by engaging in a transparent process of accountability. The Regional Rights and Resources Team has developed a comprehensive guide called \u201cCEDAW Roadmap: A Guide to Reporting before the Committee\u201d, which is intended to assist Pacific Governments in developing their CEDAW Reports. A summary of the roadmap is provided in Figure 1 on the following page. Figure 1: RRRT Roadmap To Reporting I n some countries, NGOs develop their own \u201cShadow Report\u201d, which provides additional and sometimes alternative information on CEDAW implementation and the adequacy of the Government\u2019s efforts. This Shadow Report can be a useful resource for legislators, in particular during a parliamentary committee review of the government\u2019s CEDAW Report. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 20 Reports by NGOs are referred to as Shadow Reports. The CEDAW Committee will only consider NGO reports if their government is appearing before the committee. NGOs can use their report to raise concerns with committee members on pressing issues. NGOs must prepare a 5-7 minute summary of their report for the oral session and a 1 page summary of pressing issues. Time may vary depending on CEDAW Committee workload. Session usually 45 minutes. This presentation is a summary of the submitted report and can also be used to update the committee on things that may have happened since writing of report. The aim of the presentation and questions is to develop constructive dialogue between the reporting states and the Committee. The committee accepts answers provided by the state party and asks no further questions. Any unanswered questions or issues are highlighted in the concluding comments. Usually two committee members are responsible for drafting of the concluding comments for each state party. These are not legally binding on states but often can lead to domestic debate on issues raised. NGOs are usually given a short time (about 10-15 minutes) to present their report to the committee before the state party appears. NGOs are also questioned on issues highlighted in the report. The committee meets and identifies which members will ask questions for each article. This is done in a closed session before the reporting state appears. NGOs \u2013 Find out which member is drafting your country\u2019s concluding comments. You may want to discuss certain issues you feel are important for G overnment to consider. There are comprehensive guidelines on how to report. Important for government to consult NGOs in this process. State Parties are required to report on the current status of women in their country at date of ratification. Preparing the Intitial Report Figure 1: RRRT Roadmap To Reporting CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 21 W hen adopting national legislation on the Convention, the Netherlands Parliament incorporated a provision into the law that requires the Government to report to Parliament every four years on the implementation of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0cbff07d-4533-4200-94f6-0c9fb0bfaffc": {"__data__": {"id_": "0cbff07d-4533-4200-94f6-0c9fb0bfaffc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5f418d483e93005fb0936bb7bebf08b762a64d25552ebc3e3973efb98be052a5"}, "3": {"node_id": "a352f053-8ece-4129-a73a-2c9b9d5eb025", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/cedaw-pocket-guide-pacific-parliamentarians", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "80cca8ef11076c79dacc257936bd3cf3f70277e3b75f8487a2a217adde38aa95"}}, "hash": "7d0e162e30e60fefd33c265cdee07e1a09a1b72da9d1fad4b082e5f2d4566b2c", "text": "the Convention before the state party\u2019s report is submitted to the UN CEDAW Committee. In the Pacific, it is most common for CEDAW Reports to be compiled by the relevant national women\u2019s ministry or department. However, this is not a requirement and indeed, practice in our region has shown that these bodies too often lack the technical and financial resources to do so on their own. CEDAW reporting is the responsibility of the State. Reporting should be a combined government effort, because it is supposed to cover all sectors, including education, health, rural development and employment. While one m inistry needs to take primary responsibility for the report, this could be the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Justice or even the Prime Minster\u2019s Office. A multi-disciplinary, multi-sectoral approach is needed, which engages bodies like the Attorney General\u2019s Office, the Economic Planning Unit, the Public Service Department and Treasury. The National CEDAW Report is submitted by the Government to the CEDAW Committee. The report is presented by a representative of the Government. The Committee discusses the report with country representatives, including civil society if they are in attendance. The CEDAW Committee eventually releases concluding observations and recommendations for action, which provide guidance on what more needs to be done to ensure proper implementation of CEDAW. CEDAW: A Pocket Guide for Pacific Parliamentarians 22 What can you do as a Parliamentarian? Ensure timely reporting: Use\ufffdQuestion\ufffdTime\ufffdto\ufffdinquire\ufffdabout\ufffdyour\ufffdcountry\u2019s\ufffd reporting\ufffdtimetable.\ufffdFind\ufffdout\ufffdwhen\ufffdthe\ufffdGovernment\ufffd last\ufffdreported\ufffdand\ufffdwhen\ufffdthe\ufffdnext\ufffdreport\ufffdis\ufffddue.\ufffd Where\ufffdreporting\ufffdis\ufffddelayed,\ufffdrequest\ufffdan\ufffdexplanation\ufffd and\ufffduse\ufffdparliamentary\ufffdprocedures\ufffdto\uff