 A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "eda22372bc91a03035bf7efea21c129f637cd6e49532d4f15b94f71c5262a786"}, "3": {"node_id": "c6113087-32c7-487c-889c-49e4dbd648c9", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "955e7d247ce79699e5584564b49b4ac0a76c0e8a98f96985d27ec47b44dcd20f"}}, "hash": "490573b4ffa9e2809729a9a2c3a883328d7e92634532992f7bec8c9ea06b560c", "text": "to live with hunger, let alone die from it. James Vernon, Hunger - a modern history (Harvard University Press, 2007) F ood riots in Haiti, Egypt, Senegal, and street protests in Bangladesh, and several Asian, Latin American and African countries. These Malthusian images shocked a world in the first decade of the 21st century. Material abun- dance had made the 20th century distinct from any other in history. Post-industrial services societ- ies came to dominate the global economy, signaling the welcome relegation of agriculture\u2019s share in gdP and a shift into higher produc- tivity activities, which raised living standards. A life of subsistence and drudgery had been the fabric of rural exis- tence through the course of his- tory. Low yields in food production generated the fears associated with reverend Thomas Malthus, whose dire predictions of food scarcity and famine were based on a projected imbalance between population growth rates and food production. This earned economics, essentially a study of prosperity, the unfortu- nate title of a dismal science. The 20th century defied many of the numerical myths of doom emanating in the 19th century. Predictions of a falling rate of profit and worker immiserisation did not materialise, nor did the threat of geometric increase of population and an arithmetic progression in food supply. Such rigid ratios were undermined by spectacu- lar increase in productivity due to the exponential expansion in the material fruits of science and technology. An example was the green revolu- tion, which was based on new, high yielding varieties of wheat and rice that led to a quadrupling of yields in the space of a few years, in the 1960s. At the global level, food was so ample that farm- ers had to be paid, in some countries, not to grow any more. World food prices showed a secular decline partly due to abundant supply and agricultural sub- sidies. The problem of food shortage seemed solved. However, even in the midst of such triumph, distributional issues gnawed at con- sciences, especially when they exploded into visible famines. The extremes of starvation and famine were typi- cally related to conflict, violence and discrimination. They were not viewed as disasters emanating in agriculture. There was enough food in the world, and countries built enough food stocks and suffi- ciently supple emergency systems to avert famines, in normal politi- cal circumstances. occasionally, dictatorships and closed societies could not react to famines but even these, by and large, had successful 1 inoculation against starvation. The role of a globalised internationalist media, as well as national informa- tion transmitting systems, in freer societies, acted as effective early warning systems against extreme hunger. Perhaps because of the success in food availability, countries invested their energies towards industry and services. These were the new frontiers of prosperity. The com- placency over food and reliance of an integrating global economy encouraged the view that coun- tries could import food and export higher value products and thus earn the foreign exchange through which they could, not only import food, but also the extra resources to make them richer. For some coun- tries, food security was neglected, and they became vulnerable to a rise in food prices. Hunger is not starvation. This was an important distinction that food complacency overlooked. The world had largely created institutions to prevent famines. yet, globally and nationally, the persistence of hunger has been ignored because of the absence of starvation. Hunger can, and does, persist in the absence of starvation. insufficient food has debilitating consequences due to nutritional deficiency. A lack of mental and physical development, handicaps the sufferer and, frequently, traps their children in a cycle of underde- velopment. A tragedy made more acute by the impressive advance in average prosperity. in the Asia-Pacific region, some of the fastest growing economies, such as india\u2019s, have hardly made a dent in malnutrition. results of the recent National Family Health Survey (2005 - 2006) revealed that 46 percent of india\u2019s children under three years are underweight. indeed, in some countries, malnu- trition has worsened in some parts of the country. For example, in cambodia and india, the number of undernourished people appears to have increased between 1995 and 1997, and 2001 and 20032. Nationalist sensitivity has often interfered with reason, as several policymakers have simply denied the existence of persistent hunger.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c6113087-32c7-487c-889c-49e4dbd648c9": {"__data__": {"id_": "c6113087-32c7-487c-889c-49e4dbd648c9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "eda22372bc91a03035bf7efea21c129f637cd6e49532d4f15b94f71c5262a786"}, "2": {"node_id": "277f4542-3b64-420c-91ed-c7979af8d7e7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "490573b4ffa9e2809729a9a2c3a883328d7e92634532992f7bec8c9ea06b560c"}}, "hash": "955e7d247ce79699e5584564b49b4ac0a76c0e8a98f96985d27ec47b44dcd20f", "text": "Furthermore, some have been too embarrassed to admit to this blot on their national success, despite overwhelming evidence. Attitudes however are changing and governments are far more open to not only acknowledging the problem but are outlining policies to tackle the causes of hunger. Neglected issues of hunger", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1169ebdb-16f8-46ca-932e-e7b8237293ba": {"__data__": {"id_": "1169ebdb-16f8-46ca-932e-e7b8237293ba", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c6173e65ad8fdf195c9fb49f9045a0d6731b6c66fe1da7e0bb48116d334ca4d5"}}, "hash": "c6173e65ad8fdf195c9fb49f9045a0d6731b6c66fe1da7e0bb48116d334ca4d5", "text": "and malnutrition have been forced into the policy limelight by the recent food price shock. rice prices have more than trebled since early 2005, wheat prices have risen by nearly 300 percent, and maize prices have risen by approximately 250 percent. There is a variety of causes under- lying these destabilising increases - drought in food exporting coun- tries such as Australia, substitution towards more profitable energy related crops, food subsidies and low prices in rich countries, which led to consumer gains in poor countries but discouraged food production and, thus, making these countries too reliant on the imports of very sensitive basic products. The rise in energy prices has played a crucial role in increasing prices of 2 inside asia-pacific transport and chemicals leading to knock on effects on food prices. These supply side shocks have been accompanied by pressures on the demand side, with rapidly rising incomes in poor countries leading to an obvious expansion in consumption. governments are scrambling for short term solutions to avoid major social and political upheaval. over the medium term, focus has returned to the forgotten hungry of the Asia-Pacific. Hunger was widespread before food prices rose, and the reasons for persistent malnutrition do not reside in price levels. Nonetheless, the rise in food prices will be felt most severely by the urban poor and those in rural areas who are net purchasers of food. The joint pressures of a food and energy price increase are already evident in higher subsidies and import bills. The strain on the political system, as well as on the fiscal and trade balance is particularly severe on the Ldcs (Least developed coun- tries) of the region. At a time when inequalities, within and amongst countries, are widening, the politi- cal and social consequences can be serious. governments have to cope with two major shocks which are not largely of their own making. yet, both the oil and food shocks need immediate management if turmoil is to be avoided. The rise in food prices however is not an unmitigated disaster across the Asia-Pacific. The likely impact can be divided into three catego- ries. The first are Asian countries who are likely to benefit, particu- larly the food exporters, such as Thailand and vietnam. The second category comprises typically of very large countries, on which the impact might not be too signifi- cant. This includes countries such as china, Pakistan and india that do not import large volumes of food. in these countries, the strains are likely to be localised, with specific communities under pressure, while at the macro level the imposition on budgets and the import bill might be relatively small. Further, for many farmers in the region, a rise in food prices will increase their incomes and provide market incen- tives to grow more food. A third category of countries com- prising Ldcs, countries in conflict and major importers of food and energy are likely to face the brunt of the price shocks. Ldcs, conflict and high importers often overlap, thus exacerbating the intensity of existing economic and political tension. 3 Combating Hunger: A seven Point Agenda A typology of the three categories of countries is illustrated in figures 1-3 with respect to rice. Figure 1 illustrates the case of food export- ers, who, like energy exporters currently, will benefit from rising food prices. Figure 2 illustrates the case of countries that are likely to be affected marginally, while figure 3 is the case of greatest concern. countries in this category face the unfortunate consequence that their inflation levels are also likely to increase much faster than oth- ers, imposing heavier costs on their poor and making these vulnerable countries even less competitive in export markets. rice is the staple diet for much of the world. it runs a close second to wheat in its importance as a food cereal in the human diet. World production of rice has risen steadily from about 136 million tons of rice (milled) in 1960 to 423 million tons in 2004. in the year 2006-07, the top six producers were china (30 percent of world produc- tion), india (22 percent), indonesia (8 percent), Bangladesh (8 percent), vietnam (7 percent), and Thailand (5 percent). The concentration of global rice production in Asia is captured in figure 4. World trade figures are very dif- ferent from those of production, as only a small part of rice pro- duced is traded internationally. For example, china and india are the top two largest producers of rice in the world, both countries consume the majority of the rice produced domestically leaving little to be", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3fd8e394-9590-4963-9e6c-49d60283d417": {"__data__": {"id_": "3fd8e394-9590-4963-9e6c-49d60283d417", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "85ad51808170717405511203875e76a2d04f70bf2d079741c90cb42cfbc8c029"}, "3": {"node_id": "4d796b26-711e-4688-8642-a3e077f5b4f4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "535452bffe2c3270d4a6e5949d0a54c6e182ebf64746d43f980effeea55c7aab"}}, "hash": "62b301501ea4c836b1f14ba458dfc1a2270954a1eb18032b2ac81fc9e3a2e654", "text": "traded internationally. The global trade in rice is about 30 million tonnes. World\u2019s largest rice exporters are Thailand (31 percent), vietnam (16 percent), india (14 per- cent), Pakistan (11 percent), United States (9 percent) and china (5 per- cent). global shares of rice exports are captured in figure 5, confirm- ing the dominance of Asia, and a relatively small surplus in North America and Western Europe. 5 Combating Hunger: A seven Point Agenda A worrying trend is that rice stocks have declined for the seventh consecutive year, to 72 million tons, which is nearly 4 million below 2006-07, and the lowest since 1983-84. The global stocks- to-consumption ratio is projected at 16.9 percent, down from 18.1 percent in 2006-07, and the lowest since 1976-77. While the story of rice production and consumption is largely Asian, wheat patterns are very different. A substantial portion of global wheat production and exports comes from North America and Western Europe (see figure 6), whose farm- ers are currently reaping a price rise windfall. 6 inside asia-pacific As figures 7 & 8 show, the over- whelming brunt of food price increase will be felt in Africa. Africa faces the dual disadvantage of high import dependency for rice and wheat, as well as a 250 percent increase in maize prices in recent years, which is one of the staple food items in the continent. Widespread malnutrition persisted across Asia even when food prices were low. Food price shocks pro- vide an opportunity to refocus development efforts. Equity, justice and humanity demand urgent attention to hunger in societies that are tasting the first fruits of mass prosperity. virtually all countries are becoming more unequal, as Asia is overtaking Latin America as the epicenter of inequity. The elimination of hunger requires a commitment to a flexible set of inter-related measures. 7 Combating Hunger: A seven Point Agenda The seven elements of an agenda for eliminating hunger are based on global experience. it must be emphasised that implementation in any country has to be nuanced and, to bear in mind characteris- tics that make specific instruments more or less efficacious: 1. Focus on targeted interventions, such as school feeding programmes in several countries, these have afforded the dual benefit of pro- viding nourishment and encour- aged children, particularly girls, to come to school. There is extensive global experience that can assist in a sound design of school feeding programmes. Some of this experi- ence is reflected in Anuradha raji- van\u2019s article, \u201cCombating Hunger: A Case for Pre-school and School Feeding\u201d, in this bulletin. 2. Judge development outcomes through hunger impact in recent years, several Asia-Pacific countries have achieved high growth but virtually no reduction in hunger. Monitoring and assessing development outcomes through a rigorous monitoring of trends in hunger will increase accountabil- ity of policy impact over five year periods. A technical paper on how a system for hunger related moni- toring of development outcomes is being commissioned by the UN. 3. Revive public investment in agriculture, at both national and international levels Several Asian countries have decreased public investment in agriculture. on average, public expenditure on agriculture has declined by 1.5 percent in the Asia-Pacific region between 1990 and 20073. reviving public investment is central to increased productivity, through a mix of quality extension services, farm to market roads, and investments in other forms of phys- ical infrastructure and application of evolving scientific knowledge to increase productivity. Similarly, increased investment in agricul- tural universities will potentially reap rewards. These research and development issues are empha- sised in the contribution of M.S. Swaminathan, \u201cChallenge of a Hun- ger Free Asia-Pacific Region\u201d. Medium and long term increases in food supplies will be generated by investments in research and exten- sion. in this respect, two institutes, central to the green revolution, are worth noting. These are the world\u2019s leading research institute on rice, the international rice research institute (irri) in the Philippines and the international Maize and Wheat improvement center (ciMMyT) in Mexico, part of the consultative group on international Agricultural research (cgiAr)4. The path breaking work of these two institutes has helped raise productivity of grain pro- duction.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4d796b26-711e-4688-8642-a3e077f5b4f4": {"__data__": {"id_": "4d796b26-711e-4688-8642-a3e077f5b4f4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "85ad51808170717405511203875e76a2d04f70bf2d079741c90cb42cfbc8c029"}, "2": {"node_id":