386b7fd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8200e775bb23ee702fab490ecfc0ca4613658c260577e56eae61be488f32aa47"}}, "hash": "4053b0c0ec5b0ca584dd13d900637cc6cfd08219dde6609b1b63fa01b48db152", "text": "fields produce six tons per hectare, while the soils of dry land agricul- ture in india, which are heavily dependent on seasonal rainfall, produce little more than three tons. it is estimated that some of the most advanced mega varieties will be in the field in around three to five years, grown on millions of hectares6. 4. Build a national and global coalition increased awareness amongst parliamentarians, civil society, media, civil servants, academics and other opinion formers has played a successful role in shap- ing policy. raising the profile of hunger as a key challenge requires pressure and accountability on behalf of the hungry. in support of national coalitions, international civil society organisations, focusing on hunger, can play a helpful role in transmitting practical, global lessons. Further, international development agencies can also support policy and resource allo- cation changes. The work being done by UN agencies such as iFAd (international Fund for Agricultural development), iLo (international Labour organization), WHo ( World Health organization), UNicEF (United Nations children\u2019s Fund) and WFP (World Food Programme) in the Asia-Pacific region is vital in achieving these objectives. The role of international civil society is noted in the article, \u201cHunger, Social 8 inside asia-pacific Equality, and Food Sovereignty\u201d by Kathleen McAfee. 5. Make primary education mandatory The absence of mandatory primary education in several Asian coun- tries is a major handicap to several objectives. countries that have invested early in primary educa- tion have better records on fertil- ity reduction, reduction in hunger and reducing child labour. The empirical evidence is overwhelm- ing. The work undertaken by UNi- cEF in mobilising political will and resources to help countries ensure a \u201cfirst call for children\u201d and to build their capacity to form appro- priate policies and deliver services for children has been an important contribution in promoting the right to a basic education. 6. Give subsidies to consumers for staple-foods There is an urgent need for gov- ernments to expand consumption subsidies for staple foods and for international organisations to increase their food aid in order to provide temporary relief to people who have been affected by the ris- ing food prices. To some extent this has been done already, with the US government, for example, increasing food aid. recently, the US congress approved a request for a $770 million increase in food aid to help those hardest hit by the global increase in food prices. other countries, including japan ($100 million), Britain ($59 million) and canada ($50 million), have also increased their food aid budgets 9 Combating Hunger: A seven Point Agenda in response to the growing global food crisis. While much of this relief will be targeted for Africa, Asian countries under strain might ben- efit too. The work undertaken by the WFP, as the food aid arm of the United Nations, in meeting emergency needs and supporting eco- nomic and social development in underdeveloped nations with severe food shortages, deserves acknowledgment. WFP works towards putting hunger at the top of the international agenda by promoting policies, strategies and operations that directly benefit the poor and hungry. The agency is seriously short of funds and has made appeals for it to be able to respond to increased emergency demands. 7. Rebuild global food policy in the long run, global food policy should move towards a regime that better reflects comparative advantage. currently, several oEcd countries dominate wheat production, partly due to subsidies. international food policy needs to be reviewed to examine the extent to which it is discouraging farmers in poor countries from producing food. Next Steps As the co chairs of the United Nations Regional Thematic Working Group on Poverty and Hunger, the FAO Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific and the UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo, with a variety of partners, are launching a year-long campaign to build a constituency for needed policy reform. This bulletin signifies the launch of a campaign that will be extensive, based on the seven point coalition of process, partnership and policy outlined above. 10 inside asia-pacific IN THE AsIA-PACIFIC REGION Food and agriCulture organisation rEgioNAL oFFicE For ASiA ANd THE PAciFic T he Asia-Pacific region con- tains 68 percent of the devel- oping world\u2019s population and 64 percent of its undernour- ished population. At 16 percent of the total world population, the prevalence of undernourishment is second only to Africa among the developing country regions (Figure 1).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c67fc508-f065-413e-a663-098e6386b7fd": {"__data__": {"id_": "c67fc508-f065-413e-a663-098e6386b7fd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Pub