 rural non-farm industries. UNdERNOURIsHMENT 11 Although the number of malnourished people in china has been reduced by nearly 50 million in the last decade, during this same period, the malnourished population in india has been reduced by only 3 million. Furthermore, there has been a marked increase of undernourished people in both South and East Asia (Figure 1). Behind hunger reduction - successes and challenges in most countries of the region, the majority of the population is rural, and most of the poor and food insecure live in rural areas. A vibrant rural economy is there- fore a pre-requisite for reducing undernourishment. The agricul- tural sector is crucial for a vibrant rural economy. Economic growth originating in agriculture can have a strong positive impact also on the rural non-farm economy through expanded demand for locally produced, non-agricultural goods while also contributing to keeping food prices low to the benefit of food security. increasing the pro- ductivity of small-scale farmers is especially important as rural labourers are more likely to spend their additional income on food and basic non-farm products and services produced in rural areas. Agricultural growth thus generates a virtuous cycle in which agricul- tural and rural off-farm activities sustain each other. Such growth can provide a powerful contribu- tion to reducing the number of undernourished, especially when initial income inequality is not too marked, and population growth is moderate. china and vietnam exemplify this process. This was achieved through strong economic and agricultural growth, with real per capita gdP increasing at an average annual rate of 8-9 percent, while per capita agricultural gdP grew by 2.5 percent and per capita food production by 5.4 percent per year, respectively. At the same time, the annual population growth rate was only one percent. on the other hand, the rest of East Asia has seen an increase of five percent in its undernourished population (Figure 2). The rapid decline in hunger and poverty in china started much earlier, originating with two major agricultural reforms in 1978. Fami- lies were permitted to lease land from the collectives and state pro- curement prices for food grain, oil crops and hogs were raised.2 Agri- cultural output and incomes rose dramatically in response, with rural per capita income increasing by 90 percent between 1980 and 1985. in addition, from 1985, rural non-farm enterprises began to expand rap- idly.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "462fed71-e05c-4802-a335-c800f129eec5": {"__data__": {"id_": "462fed71-e05c-4802-a335-c800f129eec5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f8b93347dc7fc214a5bbb368c0a4e36257ec75bb6445a8388eed6cdfc450f200"}, "2": {"node_id": "9028f7d0-680c-4acb-9976-0131fd142736", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "45b94a5aba84ae2bdcf9ae16ad59d0102f1f57aea415e295b2af48f31f5ac84c"}}, "hash": "a6e15f75aa82f17b48eda87234eaed71892f52d7ea680f62eb637ddfd95cfc5c", "text": "By 2000, they absorbed about a quarter of the rural labour force and contributed about 30 percent to the national gdP, while farm 12 inside asia-pacific households were deriving almost 50 percent of their incomes from non-farm sources.3 The number of poor people in rural china fell from about 490 million in 1979 to about 90 million in 2002, using the World Bank\u2019s dollar-a-day poverty line.4 The number of undernourished people was reduced from 387 mil- lion in 1969-71 to the current 150 million. The rate of hunger reduction in china has slowed in the second half of the 1990s, possibly due", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "126f6896-6159-4348-949d-67ab7caf8c90": {"__data__": {"id_": "126f6896-6159-4348-949d-67ab7caf8c90", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c1580794b12944985f413a2099047e88fc4aa8223123a64ed7d36717c89ccfad"}, "3": {"node_id": "fdefc7e2-4996-4320-a5c0-e83a71a1a79f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e73a115e62fd2c044e4f2e54184534598912296bb88d7d9a067e9c4fba525e87"}}, "hash": "ff8ac3c3ffbb58046f61d090795728b3b6fefd4ca6df9c679cdf2c4df5339124", "text": "to a wid- ening gap between the economic performance of urban versus rural areas. The majority of the remain- ing undernourished people are located in relatively isolated and disadvantaged rural areas. The bulk of agricultural output comes from about 200 million very small farms - 0.65 hectares or less.5 recent steps by the government of china to revitalize the rural areas holds out the promise that hunger reduction can accelerate in the next decade. Between 1990-92 and 2001-2003, vietnam reduced the prevalence of undernourishment from 31 to 17 percent and the number of undernourished people from 21 million to 14 million. As in china, accelerated hunger and poverty reduction originated with market- oriented economic and agricultural reforms, which were implemented starting in the 1980s. Also as in china, the drivers were strong per capita growth in gdP (5.9 percent per year) and agricultural gdP (2.8 percent per year) as well as rapid expansion in food production. vietnam remains a low-income country, and keeping a strong hun- ger reduction rate is a formidable challenge. china and india have the highest number of undernourished people in Asia and the Pacific, with 150 million and 212 million people respectively (Figure 1). However, East Asia (excluding china) and South Asia (excluding india) con- tain a proportionally higher level of malnourishment with 13 percent and 26 percent respectively (Figure 2) as compared to the rest of the region. cambodia and india saw virtually no change in the total number of undernourished people despite strong growth in per capita income - 4 percent per year from 1993 to 2003 in cambodia and 3.9 percent per year from 1990-92 to 2001-03 in india. However, the good overall economic performance was not evenly spread among sectors and not underpinned by strong agricul- tural growth; per capita agricultural gdP increased at an annual rate of only 0.7 percent from 1993-2003 in cambodia and by 1.3 percent from 1990-92 to 2001-03 in india. Per capita food and agricultural production has stagnated in india since 1999. With the consequent stagnation in rural incomes, there was no progress in reducing the population of undernourished people, which on the contrary appears to have increased between 1995-97 and 2001-03 (Figure 1). 13 Undernourishment in the Asia-Pacific Region C H A l l E N G E of A Hunger free ASiA-PAcific region M S SWAMiNATHAN cHAirMAN, M S SWAMiNATHAN rESEArcH FoUNdATioN T he Asia-Pacific region is rich in natural resources but, ironically, it is also the home of millions of malnourished and under-nourished children, women and men. An analysis conducted by FAo in 2007, on the occasion of the mid-point towards achieving the UN Millennium development goal relating to reducing poverty and hunger by half by 2015, reveals that the proportionate progress made by most countries in the region, except china, is inadequate. How then can the countries in this region achieve the goal by 2015? Hunger in the Asia-Pacific region has three major dimensions - chronic hunger caused by inad- equate purchasing power; hidden hunger caused by the deficiency of micronutrients like vitamin A, iron, iodine, and Zinc in the diet, and transient hunger caused by dis- ruption in communication due to drought, floods, cyclones, and so on. Therefore, any hunger reduc- tion strategy has to accord concur- rent attention to the elimination of chronic, hidden and transient hunger. Also, the emphasis has to shift from food security at the aggregate level to nutrition security at the level of each individual. Nutrition security is best defined as physical, economic, environmental and social access to balanced diet, safe drinking water, environmental hygiene, primary health care and primary education. This implies that there is a need for integrated attention to the food and non-food components of nutrition security. in order to achieve the goal of avail- ability of adequate food in the mar- ket at affordable prices, it is essential 14 inside asia-pacific to pay attention to enhancing the productivity and profitability of major farming systems, on an envi- ronmentally sustainable basis. This process was termed by the author about 20 years ago as an \u201cEver- green revolution\u201d.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fdefc7e2-4996-4320-a5c0-e83a71a1a79f": {"__data__": {"id_": "fdefc7e2-4996-4320-a5c0-e83a71a1a79f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c1580794b12944985f413a2099047e88fc4aa8223123a64ed7d36717c89ccfad"}, "2": {"node_id": "126f6896-6159-4348-949d-67ab7caf8c90", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ff8ac3c3ffbb58046f61d090795728b3b6fefd4ca6df9c679cdf2c4df5339124"}}, "hash": "e73a115e62fd2c044e4f2e54184534598912296bb88d7d9a067e9c4fba525e87", "text": "An Evergreen revolution involves enhancement of productivity in perpetuity, with- out associated ecological or social harm. The strategy for achieving an Ever- green revolution should have the following three components and i would like to describe them, taking india as a case study. defending the Gain The Punjab-Haryana-Western Uttar Pradesh region is india\u2019s bread basket. Punjab farmers provide 60 percent of wheat and 40 percent of rice to the Public distribution System (PdS) and national buffer stocks. The net productivity has increased in Punjab in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a6d10941-3375-4bf1-9281-bf231b820455": {"__data__": {"id_": "a6d10941-3375-4bf1-9281-bf231b820455", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ce3b8ca29aa0f6c2b7bc1121edeb07b75cab421bf2b7c291872f58d4b18228ac"}, "3": {"node_id": "ee43a39a-8150-47cf-9e2c-100fd12584b7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bf94481ed8f77bb1e0a00fe6c44d5a1897415515da74bb08dd7345e545cc3b9e"}}, "hash": "b50914f2e16b12aeeaf5f923b8a3ce40f2490f84991ec342c188cad26d5307ca", "text": "rice and wheat from 1.2 t/ha1 and 1.1 t/ha to 4.3 t/ha and 3.9 t/ha respectively from 1960-61 to 2004-05. However, in recent years there is stagnation in productivity due to a variety of causes of which the following are important: declining farm size and income. depleting natural resources base, as for example a steep fall in ground water table and impaired water quality. increasing input costs, par- ticularly diesel and adverse economics of farming. deficiency of micro-nutrients in the soil and deteriorating soil health. inadequate post harvest technology. Uncertain market prospects except for wheat and rice, though a Minimum Support Price (MSP) is announced for the following 25 agricultural commodities: \ufffd cereals - paddy, rice, wheat, jowar (sorghum), bajra, (millet), maize, ragi, barley. \ufffd Pulses - chickpea, pigeon pea, moong bean, lentil. \ufffd oilseeds - groundnut, soyabean (yellow/black), rapeseed and mustard, sunflower seed, safflower, nigerseed. \ufffd Sugarcane, cotton, jute, tobacco. High indebtedness of farm- ers - the total debt of Punjab farmers for instance is esti- mated to be about rs. 24,000 crores. (1 crore; 10 Million rupees; one US dollar = 40 indian rupees). Similar conditions prevail in the Haryana and Western UP region. Thus, the heartland of the green revolution is in grave ecological and economic trouble. These areas need conservation farming, which will help farm families to conserve and improve soil health, water quantity and quality and biodiver- sity. Some of the eco-technologies developed by the Punjab Agricul- tural University are bed sowing of wheat saving 20 to 25 percent water, leaf colour chart saving 15 percent Nitrogen application in rice, tensiometer-based irrigation scheduling, zero tillage technol- ogy for wheat, and integrated Pest Management (iPM) in cotton saving 40 percent pesticides. Thus, there is vast scope both to promote green Agriculture and to reduce the cost of production through enhanced factor productivity. A course on Sustainability Science should be introduced in all agricultural univer- sities. india will not be able to main- tain a stable food security system, if the \u201cfertile crescent\u201d (i.e. Punjab, Haryana and Western UP) region is not saved through adequate support for conservation farming. defending the gains already made in this region is an urgent task. This will require education, social mobilisation and regulation. Another area, which requires urgent attention, is adaptation to climate change. Every country in this region should develop a good Weather code to maximise the benefits of adequate moisture availability, a drought code to minimise the adverse impact of drought, and a Flood code both to prevent excessive distress and damage, and to promote a post- flood production plan. An example of the activity that can be under- taken under a good Weather code is the raising of nurseries of appro- priate plants, so that in years of excessive rainfall, an extensive tree planting and sand dune stabilisa- tion drive can be launched in arid areas. This will help to strengthen the ecological infrastructure of the desert, and gradually convert the desert into an oasis. The drought code should include the adoption of crop life saving technologies and contingency plans to change the cropping pattern according to moisture availability. \u201cBe prepared\u201d - both to take advantage of a good monsoon and to reduce the impact of adverse seasons - should be the motto in agriculture. To implement alternative cropping strategies, depending on weather conditions, a seed reserve of the substitute 15 Challenge of a Hunger Free Asia-Pacific Region crops should be maintained. just as grain reserves are essential for food security, seed reserves are necessary for crop security. Extending the Gains Eastern india (Eastern UP, Bihar, chattisgarh, orissa, West Bengal, Assam and NE States) has a large untapped production reservoir even with the technologies now available. in these areas, poor water management, rather than water availability, is the major con- straint. The indo-gangetic plains offer scope for becoming the major bread basket of india through a synergetic mix of technology, ser- vices and public policies.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ee43a39a-8150-47cf-9e2c-100fd12584b7": {"__data__": {"id_": "ee43a39a-8150-47cf-9e2c-100fd12584b7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ce3b8ca29aa0f6c2b7bc1121edeb07b75cab421bf2b7c291872f58d4b18228ac"}, "2": {"node_id": "a6d10941-3375-4bf1-9281-bf231b820455", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b50914f2e16b12aeeaf5f923b8a3ce40f2490f84991ec342c188cad26d5307ca"}}, "hash": "bf94481ed8f77bb1e0a00fe6c44d5a1897415515da74bb08dd7345e545cc3b9e", "text": "in many of these areas, the aquifer should be enriched during the South West Monsoon period, and extensive groundwater use should be pro- moted during the october-April period. given the right strategy, the ganges Water Machine could become the main anchor for india\u2019s food security system. Bihar, in particular, is a sleeping giant in the field of agriculture. Here, water managem