ty breakthroughs in major crops through genomics and gene pyramiding. For example, Super Wheats capable of yielding about 8 t/ha are now in the breeders\u2019 assembly line. Such wheats have a complex pedigree and illustrate the importance of genetic resources, conservation and exchange. Super Wheats are semi-dwarf with robust stem, broad leaves, large spikes with more number of grains per panicle and more grain weight. The Super Wheat architecture, in the breed- ers\u2019 assembly line, is derived from a blend of Tetrastichon (yugosla- via), Agrotriticum (canada), Tetra- ploid Polonicum (Poland) gigas (israel), Morocco Wheat (Morocco) and semi-dwarf wheats, currently grown in india. if we are to achieve a green revo- lution in rain-fed areas, the first important requisite is opportunity for assured and remunerative mar- keting for dry land farm products like pulses, oilseeds, millets, veg- etables, fruit, milk and meat. The decision to purchase and include ragi, millet, sorghum and other 16 inside asia-pacific nutritious cereals and millets in the Public distribution System should be an integral part of the food security system. This will help to enhance nutrition security on the one hand, and productivity and economic sustainability of improved dry land agriculture, on the other. There is a large untapped reservoir of dry land farming technologies and we can see a drastic rise in the productivity and production of crops in these areas if farm families are supported by credit, insurance, fair price and assured market for their produce. 17 Challenge of a Hunger Free Asia-Pacific Region Knowledge and Technology in Villages to Raise Agriculture Production organisation is the greatest human invention of all time. organisation is the social technology through which human beings accomplish together far more than can be accomplished individually. The Asia-Pacific region has rich experience in organising agricultural production programmes based on a win-win situation both for the environment and food security. What policy makers should never forget is that if farm ecology and economics go wrong, nothing else can go right in agriculture. in most countries in this region, a famine of sustainable livelihood opportunities, rather than availability of food in the market, is responsible for household food insecurity. Therefore, a major effort is needed to create skilled non-farm employment opportuni- ties, which are market-driven. Starting from the industrial revo- lution in Europe, the rich-poor divide started to grow because of the technology divide. Today, the technological, genetic, digital and gender divides are widening among and within nations. if technology has been a prime-mover of economic divide so far, the challenge now is to enlist technology as an ally in the movement for social and gender equity. Social inclusion in access to relevant technologies should be the bottom line of technology develop- ment and dissemination policies. i would like to cite one example to illustrate how this can be done. Urban-rural digital divide can further deepen the prevailing economic divide. Therefore, in india, a national village Knowledge centre (vKc) movement was started at the begin- ning of this century. The vKc move- ment has three components: At the level of each Block (i.e. a cluster of villages) a village resource centre (vrc) is established with satellite connectivity by the indian Space research organisation. Each village Knowledge centre (within the vKr) with internet connection is estab- lished in every village. The vKcs are managed by local men and women. The information provided is demand driven, dynamic and location spe- cific. it is in the local language. The rural families have a sense of owner- ship, since they provide the space for the centre and identify the vil- lage Knowledge workers who will run the centre. Knowledge involves conversion of generic information into a location specific one. it covers all aspects of rural life - agriculture, commerce, weather, health and edu- cation. While the green revolution helped to improve the productivity and production of wheat, rice, maize and other crops, the rural knowledge revolution helps to enhance human productivity, in all its dimensions.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6808d240-ef4c-4280-93ae-c685d3f7f5d1": {"__data__": {"id_": "6808d240-ef4c-4280-93ae-c685d3f7f5d1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "13adb9a5acfb01182728fc36e40a7dfd7bc1ae720958eac740dad88880b6e119"}, "2": {"node_id": "7f7c3cfe-6ccb-424b-8d8f-544b7fe83ea8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "079fdddb343689934ac80f54a07a495195395ab669376b316fe26ce298263380"}}, "hash": "67abd9827c19607fe814a5c2f9d17fb14692bb009f0bd18f88a7f5196a67fdef", "text": "What is significant is that the torch bearers of the rural knowledge revo- lution are rural men and women. The last mile and last person connectiv- ity will be through internet - com- munity radio or cell phone synergy. cell phones are particula