ion. This type of initiative can be further strength- ened if a community or village cluster has a Sustainable Nutrition Security System (SNSS). There are some key actions that need to be taken in order to create an SNSS. They include reorganising the delivery of nutrition support programmes on a life-cycle basis with the participation of local communities and eliminating micro- nutrient-deficiency-induced hid- den hunger through an integrated food-cum-fortification approach as well as promoting the establish- ment of community Food and Water Banks operated by Women Self-Help groups, based on the principle \u2018Store Grain and Water Everywhere\u2019; spread- ing the growth of community man- aged water budgeting systems, which will help to ensure water secu- rity for agriculture industry, domestic needs and ecosystem maintenance. Through assistance to small and marginal farmers to improve the productivity, quality and profitabil- ity of farm enterprises and through the organisation of rural Non-Farm Livelihood initiatives, rural families will have multiple sources of income. This can be achieved through the introduction of support systems to Self Help groups (SHg) to make them economically and organisa- tionally sustainable. SHg capacity Building and Mentoring centres must be established for this purpose as well as a focus on developing Micro-credit Banks into Sustainable Livelihood Banks. Finally, the formu- lation of a National Food Guarantee Act that has the useful features of the Food for Work and Employment guarantee programmes can be a powerful tool in achieving the goal of a hunger-free nation. By increasing demand for food grain as a result of increased consumption by the poor, the economic conditions, essential for further agricultural progress, can be created. 18 inside asia-pacific KatHleen mCaFee dEPArTMENT oF gEogrAPHy, UNivErSiTy oF cALiForNiA, BErKELEy HUNGER, sOCIAl EQUAlITy, ANd FOOd sOVEREIGNTy A globAl civil Society PerSPective Producing Food or Producing Money? To address the Mdg challenge to halve hunger, we must face two facts: (1) most of the world\u2019s food is still produced by small-scale farmers for family subsistence and domestic markets; however, (2) a fast-growing proportion of farm- ing worldwide is carried out for the main purpose of making profits. in what scholars describe as the global corporate food regime, a handful of transnational firms dominate food production, processing, transport, and retailing.1 The WTo Agree- ment on Agriculture, the terms of some structural adjustment loans and bilateral and regional trade treaties require liberalisation of farm and food trade policies. This means that developing-country governments may not maintain farm programmes, price supports, or import restrictions designed to protect their own domestic food producers. Studies show a connection between trade liberalisation and hunger in marginalised communities in the Asia-Pacific region. in some cases, poor farmers have no choice but to sell their food before it can be eaten. For example, indonesia has become one of the world\u2019s largest importers of rice. debt is common for smallholder indonesian rice farmers who are unable to adapt to global competition and chang- ing markets. A recent study shows that many indonesian rice farmers sell their rice before harvest to pay back debt, which results in hunger and malnutrition.2 in other cases, specialisation, combined with rapid shifts in farm gate prices, can lead to hunger and malnutrition. For example, corn was sometimes 19 found rotting in the field in Min- danao, Philippines because the domestic price was too productive to warrant harvesting the crop, leaving the poorest families with- out the cash to buy other food.3 Hunger should not be accepted as an unfortunate externality. We must take a second look at the global food system and its link to hunger.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "af4135e5-3fe4-447b-bfa4-459aebb11c90": {"__data__": {"id_": "af4135e5-3fe4-447b-bfa4-459aebb11c90", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1ccd8352614d41207ece6188d989835c75222ef436066afe18382a5ffd7c88e2"}, "2": {"node_id": "c3b6a265-6e3d-441c-b47f-44e6a27a4911", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "967e13e05881a63ff83e2f50f16e623b2f632c57cee96e88572f58f1e2ce5ede"}}, "hash": "68ae3a199ecacc6198427057bb7941d59f897442bc622bb78d0f595bef6ed302", "text": "We must take a second look at the global food system and its link to hunger. The International Movement for Food sovereignty The concept of food sovereignty entered international policy debates when it was put forward at the 1996 World Food Summit by the international farmers\u2019 confed- eration, La via campesina.4-5 Food sovereignty has become a banner uniting farmers and other agricul- ture-related movements as well as international networks of non- government organisa- tions. These alliances have been working for a decade to right injustices built into the rules of the new global architecture of agriculture. To this end, they are develop- ing alternatives to the Agreement on Agricul- ture, the Trade-related intellectual Property (TriPS) regime, and other policies that subordinate ecologies, human needs, and collective and cultural rights to the logic of profit. Food sovereignty is a central principle in these", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "54631e24-e914-4c03-b899-a01765a8e632": {"__data__": {"id_": "54631e24-e914-4c03-b899-a01765a8e632", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "db644a1aeae6a99f8e7e3ad9b9ec48ef0c7963765345d45cc63373157ac3033f"}}, "hash": "db644a1aeae6a99f8e7e3ad9b9ec48ef0c7963765345d45cc63373157ac3033f", "text": "alternatives.6 A simple definition of food sov- ereignty is the ability of countries and communities to control their own food supplies: to have a say in what is produced, under what con- ditions, and to have a say in what is imported and exported. At the local level, food sovereignty entails the rights of rural communities to remain on the land and to continue producing food for themselves and for domestic and other markets if they so desire. \u201cSovereignty\u201d, as conceived by these advocates, does not apply only to nations, but leaves room for various patterns of autonomy and interdependency at the community, regional, and global levels. Proponents of food sovereignty maintain that human rights, such as the right to food, recognised in the 1966 international covenant on Economic, Social and cultural rights, must take priority over WTo rules. While new rules enforce nar- rowly defined economic criteria for trade regulation, a food sovereignty strategy would advance the rights of governments and consumers to use broader, multiple criteria in trade and development planning. Food sovereignty would permit governments to take decisions about imports, exports, invest- ment, credit, and land and water use in ways that discriminate in favour of standards for ecologi- cal sustainability, humane animal treatment, gender equity, fair labour practices, maintenance of natural and on-farm biodiversity and other goals. it would provide a context for commodity supply management: multilateral negotia- tion to end the cycle of desperate competi- tion, gluts, and price crashes that has pulled farmers and countries into deeper debt. Food sovereignty is an alternative economic paradigm. its propo- nents contend that decentralised, diverse, and locally adapted farming systems can be more environmen- tally sustainable than a globalised food system. Where livelihoods and family goals are tied to the longer-term health and productivity of the land, they say, farmers have more incentive to conserve and improve soils, land- scapes, and water systems. By con- trast, in a globalised food system dominated by agribusiness, the competitive imperative to maxi- mise profits compels companies to externalise their environmental costs, shifting them onto the public and future generations. 20 inside asia-pacific \u00bb the elimination of food com- modity dumping (crops sales for less than the cost of production) and the right of countries to protect them- selves from predatory under- pricing and import surges. National and international policy changes, especially the banning of export subsidies, to limit overproduction and dumping are vital, as well. \u00bb the use of domestic reserves, national planning, and global supply management to ensure adequate but not excessive food production and access as well as raising farm-gate prices. land reform of a kind that \u00bb recognises the individual or collective rights of food pro- ducers, does not saddle them with debt, and puts neglected lands to productive use. \u00bb living wages and safe working conditions for agricultural and food-sector workers. The following rights must also be ensured: \u00bb those which would allow countries to prevent the ruin of domestic food producers and to foster rural development by means such as import controls - quotas, tariffs, or price band systems - and preferential agricultural credit. \u00bb access to water, regulating food and farming in the public interest. \u00bb requiring labels stating the origins and production meth- ods of foods and crops. \u00bb regulating food and farming in the public interest at the municipal, state and national governments. \u00bb deciding whether to accept genetically modified food imports or aid and whether and on what terms to permit the use of genetically engi- neered crops. \u00bb saving seeds for exchange, replanting and improving and making full use of patented crop varieties. There is currently little support for academic study and policy work in support of a food sovereignty approach. interest in such options has been inhibited by a set of myths that have gone unquestioned for too long: the myth that trade in itself, in an unequal world, will bring development benefits and the reduction of hunger; the belief that only high-chemical input industrial agriculture can feed the world\u2019s population; the illusion that small and medium-scale farms are necessarily less productive and less efficient; the notion that farmer- centered agriculture represents a turn away from science; and the idea that farmers care little about and are inevitably at odds with the natural environment. The \u201cfree\u201d trade myth is fading fast in light of the failures of two decades of trade liberalisation to reduce the numbers of hungry and poor. Technology-centred agricultural research and extension has brought no significant break- through towards greater produc- tivity since the green revolution. The excess productivity that has been achieved by", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3b1d82b4-7e75-4d82-8593-b30d572d2455": {"__data__": {"id_": "3b1d82b4-7e75-4d82-8593-b30d572d2455", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "032f9189749e4b877f2c9eb2b4362d953f62cffbcdb223d59037a2e5910f0a95"}}, "hash": "032f9189749e4b877f2c9eb2b4362d953f62cffbcdb223d59037a2e5910f0a95", "text": "other means - agribusiness subsidies, the exten- sion of agriculture to new land, and the heavy use of fertiliser - has not led to reduced hunger. domestic subsidies in many oEcd countries, in particular, have been responsible for depressing the global prices of several commodities. From the perspective of civil society organi- sations and developing countries, this has been a crucial issue. Proposals to implement food sovereignty and realise the human right to food include: 21 Hunger, social Equality, and Food sovereignty Positive Alternatives and signs of Change in the midst of the crisis caused by globalised industrial agriculture, there are some very significant and promising counter-trends. People are looking for alternative principles, policies and practices. Policymakers and citizens around the world are questioning free- market fundamentalism as well as centralised \u201csocialism\u201d, looking for better ways to understand the global economy and manage the distribution of its resources. Major international declara- 1. tions and policies of some national, regional, and munici- pal governments now rec- ognise that food is a human right. The vital principles of economic and social human rights, potentially radical in their implications but, for long, mere abstractions in the fine print of international accords, are finally being elaborated in practical terms. Tangible alternatives for farm- 2. ers are emerging in the form of systems for fair trade and cer- tification (ecological and social good-practice labels), inter- national producer-consumer networks, local processing of crops such as coffee, chocolate, and fruits to add more value to farm exports, and planning for sustainable regional develop- ment. Many options are arising from below, from the real-life experiences of farmers and other producers, often sup- ported by locally-based Ngos, scientists, and young activists rather than being imposed from outside or from above. countries are breaking away 3. from the neoliberal consen- sus: many governments and many more social movements are now resisting \u201cfree\u201d trade pressures involving food. Agro-ecological knowledge 4. for sustainable farming is deepening, enriched by local farmers\u2019 experimentation and knowledge and spreading to hundreds of thousands of new farmers every year. We now know that agroecology and related practices can produce food abundantly, reliably, and sustainably and can help guar- antee that those who need food can obtain it. Although seldom reported, there are a growing number of such suc- cesses in the global North and South. The principle of food sover- 5. eignty is gaining adherents around the world. 22 inside asia-pacific Out of a total 854 Mn undernourished people in the world, 820 Mn live in developing regions. 524 Mn lives in Asia and the Pacific, representing 61% of the total. The largest numbers live in China and India. Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Facts Hunger Fa