eases and deaths. With widespread malnutrition, small body sizes, as a result of growth fal- tering, appear \u2018normal\u2019, becoming invisible to an untrained observer. Under these conditions, the use of grain for biofuels rather than food is also a source of growing debate. Agricultural subsidies that not only inhibit fair trade but also 28 inside asia-pacific act as disincentives to farmers from developing countries are increas- ingly controversial.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "57b951c3-da3a-4e55-820f-0d0d28f3630a": {"__data__": {"id_": "57b951c3-da3a-4e55-820f-0d0d28f3630a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c4df02804a34dc36c42aa3788ccbc4c74754e958ca13ad667289c08827e98c1b"}, "2": {"node_id": "cb15c6ee-89c7-4a60-af09-500bbd402a1a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c6f207a399b2b17e21bdec0692594a0476bfbb2bf43099f94db3ce929c048100"}}, "hash": "92dd03f5921513fd8a90495ed2a3756b98b03cb8897a63da6ca9b224b635f4bf", "text": "countries can become vulnerable to social unrest in circumstances of extreme stress on the food front. concerns about food security and rising food prices are being voiced nationally and internationally. governments around the world have used dif- ferent methods to create food security - food production, buffer stocks of grain, dual pricing with price stabilisation for farmers and consumers, public distribution net- works, employment schemes, and direct nutrition investments. in this feature, we focus on direct nutri-", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "55199a66-abec-46ef-b645-4c85d8d33edc": {"__data__": {"id_": "55199a66-abec-46ef-b645-4c85d8d33edc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8cad23a3c2d2ff99868591274edc208c88ff373038e9e64ab2bd87ad4bfb3fa1"}, "3": {"node_id": "d843c982-cfb6-4840-9d48-31be68cbcb32", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c84ad6179c9304dbe9d46b55aa32804fc5e67de2b5e5067429a7c38b76f5b17c"}}, "hash": "6777f8aa10623293546a505b130d5572517b876e368c287e43312c9f4925fbb6", "text": "tion investments through school and pre-school feeding schemes that are often resisted by govern- ments but most popular with the poor. Besides governments, donors also look upon these investments unfavourably. So, if you feel that these investments are a waste of time and resources, you are not alone! in the next sections of this paper, we invite readers to reflect on evidence presented for a change on this position. For development programming, important policy questions around direct food interventions are on effectiveness, potential, limitations and examples of good practice. Problem areas to be considered are limited political will, inadequate resources, and governance gaps. Among developing countries, the indian case has relevance for other countries as direct food interven- tions have been used as a policy instrument with some success. With a population of 1.1 billion, india is akin to 25 developing coun- tries, displaying extreme contrasts. The case demonstrates that overall growth, including income poverty reduction, may not automatically translate into a reduction of mal- nutrition. While gdP growth rates have been high (9 percent in 2006) and national poverty share has declined, malnutrition is at least twice as much as the incidence of poverty. does Right to Food Make sense? conceptually, the right to food is significantly less clear than other rights like the right to information or to free speech. Who does one enforce it against and how? can parents be held liable? can society or the State at large? is it practical to punish poor parents? right to food is rather like the right to education - another right not well understood. yet, once it gets social legitimacy, it does come about. No one today questions children being in school full-time, not being part of the labour force, unlike the days of the industrial revolution. When people come to expect and demand it as a matter of course, state policies tend to respond, making it a de facto right. in india, the right to education has been incorporated into the constitution and, in 2008, there is renewed interest in updat- ing relevant legislation. right to food, however, is yet to be recog- nised as such. 29 Combating Hunger : A Case for Pre-school and school Feeding Nevertheless, in 2001, india\u2019s Supreme court responded to a public interest litigation and ordered all government and government-assisted primary schools to provide cooked midday meals for school students and pre- schoolers below six years old. Parents can demand meals and enforce them through courts if neces- sary, placing the onus on governments. None of the state governments in india liked it, as it was considered a budgetary and organisational nightmare. scaling up India\u2019s Pioneer state Experience: Tamil Nadu, a pioneer state. india\u2019s case makes an interesting study, not only because of its size and diversity, but also because it has been scaled-up from a single pioneer state, Tamil Nadu (TN). The case demonstrates key principles for success and can help identify limitations and continuing problem areas of relevance to help other countries of comparable popula- tion such as Nepal, Sri Lanka, the Philippines and Bangladesh4. More- over, TN is india\u2019s first state to have, in place an official policy crafted in consultation with UNicEF (2003) for making the state malnutrition free by 2020. This official policy is backed by budgets through a combination of state funding and central allocations. TN near-universalised feeding for the nutritionally vulnerable through public funding well before judicial intervention. While the state has a long history of providing food outside the home for young children and mothers, it was not until 1982 that for the first time, the hardest to reach group was included - preschoolers between two to five years old. At first, nutri- tion-oriented schemes and hun- ger-oriented schemes operated in parallel, but were later combined. Today, the nutrition-cum-child- development programme is well entrenched in the state. Food has become an integral part of the school and pre-school rou- tines in villages and urban wards. A midday meal is provided to chil- dren with supplementary feeding to those below 24 months. certain categories of nutritionally-vulnera- ble adults like pregnant and nurs- ing women, the destitute and old are also entitled to a hot midday meal every day. other links have been established, like health, such as growth monitoring, immunisa- tion, deworming, vitamin A, iron and folic acid supplementation.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d843c982-cfb6-4840-9d48-31be68cbcb32": {"__data__": {"id_": "d843c982-cfb6-4840-9d48-31be68cbcb32", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8cad23a3c2d2ff99868591274edc208c88ff373038e9e64ab2bd87ad4bfb3fa1"}, "2": {"node_id": "55199a66-abec-46ef-b645-4c85d8d33edc", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6777f8aa10623293546a505b130d5572517b876e368c287e43312c9f4925fbb6"}}, "hash": "c84ad6179c9304dbe9d46b55aa32804fc5e67de2b5e5067429a7c38b76f5b17c", "text": "over 70,000 centres function every day, covering around 8,000,000 persons. in spite of its sheer scale, the programme has grown and stabilised. Three features of this experience are noteworthy. First, there has been sustained political will from above resulting in public policy attention on hunger", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4d5882e2-eea3-4aa4-9d8c-6f7aea0ea81b": {"__data__": {"id_": "4d5882e2-eea3-4aa4-9d8c-6f7aea0ea81b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ba78c3adc52556afb020146f698f5707fc57564859ca682602a14ac22b4f22e9"}, "3": {"node_id": "de416aa1-5c94-4efe-aa41-d7f64699065f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "442f13c3e796a265374a296d86b4ce3cef7139a0d59f29f1c25dd59fb21b40a8"}}, "hash": "b893c7657bd5d5f2be1f506db07cbd8664ded938855693222f144eaf3979bcaf", "text": "and malnutri- tion with budgetary allo- cations. Second, there has been pressure from below with the programmes becoming so well accepted that it is difficult to let a facility remain closed for any length of time with- out local reaction and enquiry. Third, pressure from beneficiaries, has in turn, contributed to the retention of political will over time regardless of the party in power. As public funding of the state-wide nutrition effort has come to stay, TN is on the verge of establishing child rights to nutrition security. However, the programme is not without its problems. issues have emerged such as population relo- cation, remote location access, staff motivation and training, and most importantly, the limited focus on prevention and participation of local communities, in design or implementation. What have been the changes in the state\u2019s nutrition profile? The sever- est forms of malnutrition seem to have almost completely disap- peared. Specifically, weight-for-age data among children participating in the World Bank Assisted inte- grated child development Service (WBicdS-iii) under 36 months of age5 show a steady decline in severe malnutrition from a little over 12 percent to half of one percent. Simultaneously, the percentage of normal children has increased from under 20 to over 50 percent. Percentages of moderate malnour- ishment have also declined. 30 inside asia-pacific Scaling up to the national level. it was public interest litigation, not political will, which resulted in gen- erating pressure at the top, at the national level (See previous section above). Most states missed the six- month deadline - they could not or did not comply. yet, this pressure from above contributed to a steady expansion of school lunches as most states, after some reluctance, began complying. While this was a victory of sorts, it soon became clear that judicial intervention needed to be supplemented by pressure from below to make it politically worth- while - linking midday meals to electoral prospects. Wider pressure is being generated through a nation- wide \u2018right-to-Food campaign\u2019 by an informal network of supporters. in some of the other states, the pic- ture was mixed due to factors such as inadequate political will, under- funding, infrastructure or manage- ment. in chhattisgarh, for example, cooking took place in soot covered classrooms, there were swarming pupils, utensils were inadequate, cooks struggled and got children to help. in rajasthan, although the political will was in place, the meal was identical every day (ghoogri - boiled wheat & jaggery) and the infrastructure was poor. Upper caste children had brought food from home, which could be the result of social discrimination or privilege, making social inequali- ties explicit. The potential of direct food interventions goes beyond the commonly understood benefits of basic survival and sustenance. Multi-dimensional effects include improvements in health status, greater demand for basic educa- tion, reduction of income poverty, decreased household expenditure for curative care, increased public savings and greater social equity, including gender equality. For example, a 2003 survey revealed that the TN model was effective in many ways as it: addressed intra-household \ufffd issues, removing existing \u2018social\u2019 biases against girls; \ufffd contributed to common dining and socialisation of children at a very early age due to univer- sal feeding; \ufffd was administratively efficient as the targeting took place automatically through location of the programme in govern- ment facilities which tended to exclude the well off; encouraged social equity \ufffd through a preference for dalits6 and widows among staff; \ufffd helped retain regularity and quality through community watch and participation. At the same time, limitations need to be recognised. Nutrition status is an outcome of a number of bio- medico-socio-economic processes interacting over time. Without understanding them, the effective- ness of food investments alone is limited. Sharing of entitlements among the non-target population, like the rest of the family, which happens with take-home dry rations, can also reduce benefits. complicated targeting in an effort to focus on the poor can add to administrative costs and vulner- ability to leakages. Area-based targeting, focusing on state funded schools and pre-schools can help. However, those out of school, the worst off, will be omitted unless separate provisions are made. As food is attractive, leakages can be expected until pressure from below facilitates social monitoring.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "de416aa1-5c94-4efe-aa41-d7f64699065f": {"__data__": {"id_": "de416aa1-5c94-4efe-aa41-d7f64699065f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ba78c3adc52556afb020146f698f5707fc57564859ca682602a14ac22b4f22e9"}, "2": {"node_id": "4d5882e2-eea3-4aa4-9d8c-6f7aea0ea81b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b893c7657bd5d5f2be1f506db07cbd8664ded938855693222f144eaf3979bcaf"}}, "hash": "442f13c3e796a265374a296d86b4ce3cef7139a0d59f29f1c25dd59fb21b40a8", "text": "As food is attractive, leakages can be expected until pressure from below 