hil- dren from better-off households prefer bringing food from home. Another set of issues arises as the concept of nutrition status is not Potential and limitations 31 Combating Hunger : A Case for Pre-school and school Feeding HOw MUCH dO dIRECT FOOd INVEsTMENTs COsT? (Table 1) Main Components: 1) capital: one time costs for infrastructure and equipment. 2) recurring: ingredients, transport, conversion costs (from raw ingredients into cooked food), and administration. 3) Maintenance: for wear and tear. An estimate for recurring cost per capita based on India\u2019s example calculated locally: grains (100g) 1.11 Transport 0.08 conversion costs (daal, veg, salt, oil, condiments, fuel, staff) 2.00 Administration 0.02 Total (approx) Rs. 3.21 or Usd 0.07 as widely understood as hunger. The shift from a drug-based to a food-based approach has been a big improvement, as nutrition is not just a matter of excess or short- age of specific nutrients. countries now need to make the next shift - to a knowledge-based approach for people to make pro-nutrition choices while dispelling inaccurate beliefs (e.g. \u201cdaals are too heavy for children\u201d thus depriving them of protein, \u201ciron tablets in pregnancy result in \u201cdark\u201d children\u201d, \u201csoda cures gas\u201d). Hence, it is very important to provide nutrition education to the target population, to complement food inputs. in recent years, a new dimen- sion has been added in terms of increased consumption of fizzy drinks and processed foods amongst urban and rural poor. rural obesity and other lifestyle diseases have become increasingly common. The poor appear to have increased spending their incomes on more expensive but nutrition- ally inferior food. Even in TN, while improvements among participants are observed, other data indicate that the overall prevalence of malnutrition in the state persists. The third National Family Health Survey (2005-06) shows that among children under five, 30 percent are underweight, 31 per cent stunted and 22 percent of newborns are categorised as low birth weight. New batches of under- weight babies further contribute to the probability of ending up malnourished. While there is fairly efficient management of exist- ing malnutrition among babies, a critical concern is how does one minimise it in new batches? Unlike drugs or food, nutrition status can- not be \u2018delivered\u2019. Costs and Financing it is easier to secure funding for one time capital expenses, while com- mitting resources for recurring and maintenance expenses is harder. Financing of these expenditures in india has been done jointly by the centre and state governments. ongoing development schemes have been used to fund parts of the costs. Local contributions are also encouraged which help commu- nity buy-in. However, not all states are contributing their expected share as political will has varied. donor financing is also an option. But, by and large, for the present, the right to food is less accepted than that for education. There seems to be a willingness to sup- port education. To that extent, rather than, food per se, Food For Education (FFE) is considered more acceptable, which more or less rules out donor financing for pre- school ages. This is a fairly strongly held posi- tion within most governments as well. Hunger is expected to be in the household realm. Hence, longer term indirect interventions like income generation have been preferred instruments. But there is an argument for direct food investments as well, more so as poverty declines have not resulted in corresponding nutritional improvements. Finally, while money is important, money alone is not enough. com- plementary policies that include institutional changes like harness- ing inter-ministerial synergies and capacity development can maxi- mise the benefit per dollar.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cb291f7c-ec09-471b-9434-01b90a39816e": {"__data__": {"id_": "cb291f7c-ec09-471b-9434-01b90a39816e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9bdf0b18a20215f15082225f973a081219dfe505bd042224563202b1e36a167f"}, "2": {"node_id": "e2168e4c-1371-41ed-b640-bc78007c518c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "130b3ee0538e355668c0d6400b8026713a52ad8186140cfe26c56d69ebde1a85"}}, "hash": "454386a817738f63a7be3f4f3326426cebf3c4c11a1331fb83dc02df718097ad", "text": "32 inside asia-pacific This paper has four overall messages: \ufffd direct nutrition interventions have the potential to address five important development concerns - poverty, hunger-nutrition, health, education and social equity; \ufffd benefits are not automatic - they depend upon the design and quality of implementation; criti- cal issues are: pressure from above and pressure from below \u2022\ufffd administrative and technical capacities \u2022\ufffd adequate budgets \u2022\ufffd \ufffd poor design and implementation can do more harm than good; \ufffd expectations should be realistic about effects as there are a number of other contributory factors to be addressed in parallel. in conclusion, we need to ask the fundamental ques- tion - should we really let people starve, in the interest of fiscal prudence when we have the technology and resources to prevent this? if not, then the recommen- dations are to follow a two-pronged strategy: prevention for those not yet malnourished; \ufffd management for those already malnourished. \ufffd in operationalising this,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9f1046ef-7f94-42f1-8d1c-c5c9e7ee644f": {"__data__": {"id_": "9f1046ef-7f94-42f1-8d1c-c5c9e7ee644f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f1312e2387d32ccc85c4aa7e32625553e0c011390ba4a732e09dc22c15c760a1"}, "3": {"node_id": "8fe91f66-63f6-4161-a852-161236dbf2e1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9de7c0287c037c121c3a83aaf8f1f905eee20416e2029333b41b92b7df1fd52f"}}, "hash": "58991c53059b46c48e336a0b211b14def58b252b0feed52bbe73e185b42e1cbf", "text": "we must customise inputs by socio-economic groups: \ufffd knowledge for the better-off to promote nutrition literacy; \ufffd subsidised inputs-cum-knowledge for the worse-off. Messages and Conclusion 33 Combating Hunger : A Case for Pre-school and school Feeding A s noted earlier in the bul- letin, hunger and malnu- trition comprise a serious threat, more deadly than malaria, tuberculosis and AidS combined. in recognition of its seriousness, the first Millennium development goal (Mdg) is devoted to halving the proportion of hungry people, by 2015.1 Ten years after the World Food Summit, the number of people afflicted by under-nutrition had risen by approximately 23 million.2 There are 854 million undernour- ished people in the world, with over 96 percent of these (820 million) in the developing World (Figure 1). The Asia-Pacific region contains the greatest proportion of undernourished population in the world (61 percent) (Figure 2). More specifically, half of all children in South Asia are suffering from malnutrition, as opposed to one in three in Sub-Saharan Africa - a more impoverished region.3 At the global level, attention to hunger has attracted greater cur- rency, although with a lack of urgency. only 24 percent of the countries are on track to achieve the nutrition target of the Mdgs. Although Asia as a whole may suc- ceed, South Asia will not. A failure to upscale the fight against hunger will impede overall progress and may \u201cderail\u201d other efforts from reaching the Mdg targets4. it is in the interests of developing nations to prioritise hunger alleviation in their poverty reduction strategies. Best practices for emulation are readily available at a small cost to governments and a supportive international community. despite the 70 percent rise in population over the past 30 years, COMBATING HUNGER A globAl PerSPective lara Brearley LoNdoN ScHooL oF HygiENE ANd TroPicAL MEdiciNE 34 inside asia-pacific agricultural produce now provides 17 percent more calories per head. As is well known, it is not an issue of availability that perpetuates hunger in the world; rather, it is the lack of access - due to ineq- uitable distribution, poverty and weak purchasing power. Nonethe- less, increasing food production should not be neglected on the complacency of sufficient global food. As emphasised elsewhere in this bulletin, several measures need to be taken to increase food production. The cycles of malnutrition are obvi- ous. Maternal malnutrition often causes low birth weight babies; correspondingly, roughly 60 per- cent of women in the region are undernourished.6 Malnutrition from conception to two years can have an irreversible effect on the child, impeding its productive capacity throughout life.7 Subse- quently, the mother\u2019s nutritional status and feeding practice for the infant are crucial. 13 As the President of Nigeria, chief o. obasanjo, aptly stated, \u201cWe have a saying in my country, when you take hunger out of poverty, poverty is halved.\u201d8 Nevertheless, hunger and poverty are by no means synonymous; interventions targeting both must be pursued in parallel. Furthermore, there are strong, pragmatic and economic incen- tives for the drive to eliminate hunger. diminished productivity, due to malnutrition, decreases an individual\u2019s lifetime income by at least ten percent. This can reduce a nation\u2019s gdP by as much as two to three percent.9 given their proven success and high returns, investments in micronutrients are relatively cheap. in the 2004 copenhagen consensus, eminent economists prioritised micronutri- ent initiatives: \u201cNo other technol- ogy offers as large an opportunity 35 Combating Hunger : A Global Perspective to improve lives at such low cost and in such a short time\u201d. 10 So why has this seemingly obvious opportunity not been seized? in some Asian countries, progress in reducing the prevalence of hunger has been alarmingly slow. This may, primarily, be attributed to political neglect. Failure to prioritise hunger alleviation in the national agenda has curtailed the allocation of sub- stantial resources to the cause. As the public sector plays \u201ca catalytic role\u201d in the fight against hunger, it is necessary for governments to revise their priorities. The victims of chronic and hidden hunger are often the poor, who have little political power. This perpetuates governmental inaction as there is minimal pressure from below.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8fe91f66-63f6-4161-a852-161236dbf2e1": {"__data__": {"id_": "8fe91f66-63f6-4161-a852-161236dbf2e1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f1312e2387d32ccc85c4aa7e32625553e0c011390ba4a732e09dc22c15c760a1"}, "2": {"node_id": "9f1046ef-7f94-42f1-8d1c-c5c9e7ee644f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "58991c53059b46c48e336a0b211b14def58b252b0feed52bbe73e185b42e1cbf"}}, "hash": "9de7c0287c037c121c3a83aaf8f1f905eee20416e2029333b41b92b7df1fd52f", "text": "This perpetuates governmental inaction as there is minimal pressure from below. How to overcome this challenge of widespread hunger in the devel- oping world? other sections of the bulletin focus on a twin-track approach, consisting of seven interventions. one prong pursues longer-term investments for struc- tural change, hunger prevention, and sustainable alleviation of malnutrition. The second prong focuses on the short-term, direct and targeted interventions, which accelerate the process and provide immediate relief from the pangs of hunger. Moreover, multi-sectoral interventions \u201care often not merely additive, but multiplicative\u201d when fighting hunger and malnutri-", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "539733d7-3b4a-4b9e-b51a-454f5d3f1ff4": {"__data__": {"id_": "539733d7-3b4a-4b9e-b51a-454f5d3f1ff4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Combating Hunger: A Seven Point Agenda", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "24d80b7c47a85182f313e67ce36a6366b7763d1920a2048d817bc27dfffb726a"}, "3": {"node_id": "68a611c5-7971-4625-b3a8-bb494792d473", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/combating-hunger-seven-point-agenda", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "11bb3e54b662e4b5823bc95408ad991e1542c26736baec5f0b02cade88699382"}}, "hash": "1a32571f26bb7aae95c4f475b5b1db27f7fc80304361bdc2863d60b59c12471e", "text": "tion.12 Whilst a balance between short and long-term interventions should be maintained, direct inter- ventions must be strengthened fast, especially in light of higher food prices. Effective and direct interventions have a demonstrated impact, but what are the global financial impli- cations of this? The Millennium Project Task Force on Hunger estimated that invest- ments to achieve the hunger-re- lated Mdgs would amount to just five to eight percent of the total cost of all eight goals. When compared with other sectoral costs, such as education at 16 percent, roads at 18 percent and health at 25 per- cent, combating hunger requires \u201cmarginal\u201d investment, and its mul- tiplier effects would accelerate the eradication of poverty.13 36 inside asia-pacific \u201cLet there be no doubt. Sport has both the ability and the responsibility to help as the world grapples with these fundamental humanitarian challenges\u201d, James Morris, former Executive director of WFP. Kevin Pietersen, ranked No. 8 in the ICC world batsmen rankings, presents a set of wickets to a child involved in the World Food Programme in Sri Lanka Photo credit: gettyimages CriCket AgAinst Hunger England cricket captain, Michael vaughan, batsmen Alastair cook and Kevin Pietersen, and coach Peter Moores led, between the Tests in colombo and galle, a coaching session for 22 children from 11 schools in the galle area on 15 december 2007. All of these children are recipients of the World Food Programme\u2019s School Feed- ing Programme in Sri Lanka, which currently provides a nutritious meal each day to approximately 350,000 children across 15 of the 25 districts. This was one of the high profile events that have taken place since the launch of \u2018cricket Against Hunger\u2019 in 2006 - a key partner- ship between the England and Wales cricket Board and the WFP, in the fight to combat child hunger around the world. \u201cThe England Team is very proud to be associated with WFP. The \u2018cricket Against Hunger\u2019 campaign gives us an excellent opportunity to help raise awareness about WFP\u2019s work. We, as players, have all enjoyed being able to put something back into the local communities we visit whilst on overseas tours with England,\u201d affirmed Michael vaughan, England Test captain. Highly acclaimed sportsmen and women have the potential to pro- mote the plight against hunger. WFP has harnessed this potential by building a multitude of partner- ships - with the England and Wales cricket Board, the international rugby Board, first class footballer ronaldinho and marathon runner Paul Tergat, to name a few. As England\u2019s players often tour countries where widespread pov- erty and hunger prevail, they are in a powerful position to promote the plight of the hungry. \u201cWe are in the public eye, and we have an oppor- tunity to tell our fans and follow- ers about the scale of this problem and the work that WFP is doing to address it,\u201d asserted Alastair cook at the galle event. WFP School Feeding Pro- grammes were introduced to Sri Lanka in 2003 and were expanded after the devasta- tion caused by the indian ocean tsunami, exacerbated the problem of child malnu- trition. \u201cThe most rewarding part of working for the WFP is to see the smiles on the faces of the children who are about to have their mid-morning meals in Sri Lanka\u2019s 1588 schools. it is great that the cricket Against Hunger HUNGER FOR CRICKET FEEds 37 For further information, please contact: gregory Barrow, WFP London gregory.barrow@wfp.org selvi sachithanandam, WFP Sri Lanka selvi.sachithanandam@wfp.org mark ward, England and Wales cricket Board mark.ward@ecb.co.uk Photo credit: gettyimages England Cricket Captain Michael Vaughn and opener Alistair Cook at the Cricket Against Hunger event at the tsunami affected city of Galle, 2007 partnership gives the opportunity to the English cricket Team to work at keeping those smiles on t